Answer:
To run a cron every 30 minutes, use the cron pattern `*/30 * * * *` in your `schedules.task()`:

```ts
import { schedules } from "@trigger.dev/sdk";

export const myTask = schedules.task({
  id: "every-30-min-task",
  cron: "*/30 * * * *",
  run: async (payload) => {
    // your logic here
  },
});
```

This is a **declarative schedule** that syncs when you run `dev` or `deploy`. You can also specify a timezone by passing an object to `cron` with `pattern` and `timezone` properties.

See [Scheduled tasks (cron)](/tasks/scheduled) for full details.

```suggestions
(Scheduled tasks (cron))[/tasks/scheduled]
(Create Schedule via SDK)[/management/schedules/create]
```

You can **exit a task early and prevent retries** by throwing an `AbortTaskRunError`. This immediately fails the task attempt and disables any further retrying.

```ts
import { task, AbortTaskRunError } from "@trigger.dev/sdk";

export const openaiTask = task({
  id: "openai-task",
  run: async (payload: { prompt: string }) => {
    const chatCompletion = await openai.chat.completions.create({
      messages: [{ role: "user", content: payload.prompt }],
      model: "gpt-3.5-turbo",
    });

    if (chatCompletion.choices[0]?.message.content === undefined) {
      throw new AbortTaskRunError("OpenAI call failed");
    }

    return chatCompletion.choices[0].message.content;
  },
});
```

Full details are on the [Errors & Retrying](/errors-retrying) page.

